   <info>  
   <p>More information on formats for long-term preservation at ARCHE is available at the information page <a href="https://arche.acdh.oeaw.ac.at/browser/filenames-formats-metadata">"Filenames, Formats, and Metadata"</a>. ARCHE uses the term "recommended" for any formats suitable for long-term preservation, which equals the level "recommended" from CLARIN. The term "accepted" refers to formats that can be acceptable for long-term preservation in specific cases ("acceptable" in CLARIN terms) or are accepted by ARCHE, but will be converted into a more suitable format; in CLARIN terms this equals "discouraged".</p>
      <p>Depositors are strongly encouraged to provide the resources in standard formats adopted by the respective research communities. ARCHE curators will support depositors in converting the data if this is necessary and feasible.</p>
      <p>Suitable formats should be widely in use and, if possible, be in compliance with open and non-proprietary standards. Files should not be password protected, encrypted or compressed in a lossy way. If files depend on references to other files, fonts, or other external data, these objects should be deposited as well, or at least described in e.g. a plain text README file. Whenever a choice for encoding is possible choose UTF-8 without the byte order mark (BOM).</p>
      <p>A more technical view on the list of accepted and recommended formats can be found in <a href="https://github.com/acdh-oeaw/arche-assets/blob/master/AcdhArcheAssets/formats.json">JSON format on GitHub</a>.</p>
   </info>
